# Effect-TS Patterns

This codebase uses Effect v4. Follow these patterns strictly.

## Services

Use `ServiceMap.Service` with `make:` property. Never `Effect.Service` or `Context.Tag`.

```ts
export class MyService extends ServiceMap.Service<MyService>()("@scope/MyService", {
  make: Effect.gen(function* () {
    const dep = yield* SomeDependency;
    const doThing = Effect.fn("MyService.doThing")(function* (input: string) {
      yield* Effect.annotateCurrentSpan({ input });
      return result;
    });
    return { doThing } as const;
  }),
}) {
  static layer = Layer.effect(this)(this.make).pipe(Layer.provide(SomeDependency.layer));
}
```

## Errors

Use `Schema.ErrorClass` with explicit `_tag`. Never `Schema.TaggedError`.

```ts
export class MyNotFoundError extends Schema.ErrorClass<MyNotFoundError>(
  "MyNotFoundError",
)({
  _tag: Schema.tag("MyNotFoundError"),
  entityId: Schema.String,
}) {
  message = `Entity not found: ${this.entityId}`;
}
```

## Error Handling

- `catchTag` / `catchTags` for specific errors
- Never `catchAll`, `mapError`, `option`, `ignore`
- Infrastructure errors become defects: `Effect.catchTags({ SqlError: Effect.die })`
- Use `.asEffect()` on error classes, not `Effect.fail(new Error(...))`

## Functions

Every effectful function uses `Effect.fn` with a span name:

```ts
const myFn = Effect.fn("myFn")(function* (arg: string) {
  yield* Effect.annotateCurrentSpan({ arg });
  // ...
});
```

## Key Rules

- Never explicitly type return types on Effect functions
- Never use `null` — use `Option` or `undefined`
- Never use `process.env` — use `Config.string` / `Config.integer`
- Prefer `Effect.forEach` over `Effect.all`
- Use `Effect.try` / `Effect.tryPromise` instead of try/catch
- Branded IDs: `Schema.String.pipe(Schema.brand("MyId"))`
